# Copy to .env and fill in. The app REFUSES TO START without VITE_RP_ID (a named error, on purpose);
# everything else is optional and falls back to sane testnet defaults.
#
# VITE_RP_ID pins the ONE origin allowed to derive this wallet's keys. A WebAuthn PRF evaluation IS
# the private key, and PRF is scoped to (credential, rpId) — NOT to the page's code — so EVERY origin
# matching this value can derive a user's keys. Pin it explicitly; never infer it from the URL bar,
# and never widen it to an apex you don't fully control: an XSS on any subdomain sharing the rpId, or
# a single subdomain takeover, is a wallet drain. `localhost` here is for LOCAL DEV ONLY — for
# anything deployed, set your real, narrow domain. A wrong rpId fails WebAuthn safely (it can't
# derive keys) rather than leaking; it just won't work.
VITE_RP_ID=
# Operator display name — optional. The friendly name shown in the passkey prompt (WebAuthn rp.name,
# the OS "Sign in to …") and as the wallet-label prefix ("<name> Wallet · Nickname"). Cosmetic only:
# it never affects the rpId or key derivation. Defaults to the rpId domain when unset.
# VITE_OPERATOR_NAME=
# Anchor chain — where THIS wallet anchors its secondary-device backup slots. Referenced by NAME
# (default: optimism = eip155:10). Any EVM chain name in the registry works — e.g. base, arbitrum,
# arc-testnet. The Home/Send screens also default their EVM view to this chain.
# VITE_ANCHOR_CHAIN=optimism
# Paymaster URL — enables EVM sponsored (sponsored tx); requires BYO ERC-4337 infra — an ERC-7677 paymaster (VITE_PAYMASTER_URL) AND an ERC-4337 bundler (VITE_BUNDLER_URL); both must be set.
# The fee TOKEN is NOT configured here: it is chain-specific, so the Send screen reads the supported
# tokens for the target chain from the registry (client.evm.feeTokens) and lets the user pick one.
# VITE_PAYMASTER_URL=https://localhost:8788
# ERC-4337 bundler URL. EVM sponsored needs BOTH this and VITE_PAYMASTER_URL (canSponsor gates on both).
# VITE_BUNDLER_URL=https://localhost:8789
# Solana cluster is NOT configured here — the Home/Send screens show a devnet/mainnet toggle and the
# SDK targets the picked cluster per call.
# Solana sponsored (sponsored) — needs a Kora fee payer (VITE_KORA_URL below). The
# fee mint is likewise read per-cluster from the registry (client.solana.feeTokens), not from env.
# Kora fee payer (Solana sponsoring). Kora is BOTH paymaster and submitter, so this one
# endpoint is the Solana analogue of VITE_PAYMASTER_URL + VITE_BUNDLER_URL together.
# Self-host with kora-cli, or point at a hosted Kora. Unset => Solana sends are self-pay.
# VITE_KORA_URL=http://localhost:8080

# --- RPC endpoints (recommended for anything but a quick local test) ---
# Avok ships NO third-party RPC provider as a default: an RPC answers "what address does
# vitalik.eth resolve to?", so a dishonest one redirects your money. You choose who to trust.
#
# Leave these unset and the demo falls back to the registry's PUBLIC endpoint. That is fine for
# poking around, but public endpoints are rate-limited, have no SLA, and REFUSE the indexed reads a
# wallet needs — they 403 or hang on getTokenAccountsByOwner, so your SPL token balances read 0.
#
# You do NOT need a backend for this. A domain-allowlisted provider key (Helius, Triton, QuickNode)
# is safe to ship in a browser bundle: it only works from your own domains. Alternatively point
# these at a proxy you host, and the key never leaves your server.
# VITE_SOLANA_RPC_MAINNET=https://mainnet.helius-rpc.com/?api-key=YOUR_KEY
# VITE_SOLANA_RPC_DEVNET=https://devnet.helius-rpc.com/?api-key=YOUR_KEY
# Advanced — per-chain EVM endpoints as a JSON map of chainId -> url:
# VITE_EVM_RPC_URLS={"8453":"https://base-mainnet.example.com/v2/YOUR_KEY"}
